## {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.molecular_formula }}

Clinical trials for evaluating new antihypertensive drug entities are usually randomized, placebo-controlled parallel group studies designed to determine that a drug has efficacy, to establish its dose–response characteristics, to measure its duration of action, and to evaluate study. Efficacy is measured by subtracting the placebo effects (which are often in the range 3 to 8 mm Hg in such trials) from those of the active drug, using the trough values obtained at the end of the dosing interval (after 24 h in the case of once daily drugs). Trough values, which may not accurately reflect a drug's blood pressure ({{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}) effects throughout the day, are also used to define dose–response relationships.

Information from clinical trials may not be completely relevant to the use of antihypertensive agents in clinical practice. First, physicians do not use placebo, but judge efficacy by comparing the {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} on a drug with the pretreatment values. Second, measurements are rarely obtained at trough, but instead are more likely to reflect the drug's peak effects that occur within a few hours of dosing. Third, unlike formal controlled trials that randomize patients to different dose groups, clinicians tend to start most of theirpatients on a relatively low dose and then use higher doses only in those patients who do not have adequate reduction in {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}. The outcomes of this practical approach are not likely to have been accurately predicted by parallel groups trials. For these reasons, open-label practice-based clinical studies may provide key information about the utility and clinical properties of antihypertensive drugs that is not available from the standard registration trials.1,2,3,4 In addition, the large number of patients typically enrolled in such studies allows a useful evaluation of safety as well as providing power to measure efficacy in different patient demographic groups.

The angiotensin receptor blockers ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) are drugs that reduce {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} by selectively blocking the actions of angiotensin II at its AT1 receptor.5,6 {{ drug.name }} is an {{ drug.molecular_formula }} with a long duration of action, and in formal clinical trials has been shown to have antihypertensive efficacy when used alone or in combination with a diuretic.7,8 The present study was undertaken to evaluate the efficacy of this agent in a community-based setting, working in collaboration with a large number of physicians with active clinical practices. The goal of the study was not only to measure safety and efficacy, but to obtain further information about how practitioners actually use drugs such as {{ drug.name }} in different types of patients. The results of this trial emphasize that useful information about the effectiveness of a drug can be obtained from studies in the community.
